Understanding the Cost of Collisions

This calculator estimates collision costs using data from two sources: the{" "} 2018 CRISP report from Edmonton {" "} and {" "} collision data from the Saskatoon Police .

For a full breakdown of the calculations, refer to the original report. This calculator is an independent project and is not affiliated with CRISP or Saskatoon Police.

The CRISP report breaks down collision-related costs into three categories:

  • Direct Costs: Expenses such as police, fire, hospitals, coroners, and insurance.
  • Human Capital: Economic losses from lost labor, congestion delays, etc.
  • Willingness to Pay (WTP): The cost society is willing to bear to prevent future collisions.

The estimated costs per collision type are as follows:

Collision Type Direct Costs ($) Human Capital ($) WTP ($)
Injury 48,341 89,408 158,654
Fatality 225,558 2,224,580 6,707,228
Property Damage 14,065 0 0

The last CRISP report was published in 2018. To account for inflation, all costs have been adjusted using a 20.84% increase based on Statistics Canada data.

); }
